  <h5 align="center">Chapter 4.</h5><h1 align="center">VISUALS</h1><br><br>

    <span class="callout">(Logos, fonts, colors)</span>
    <p>
      A logo is another expression of the brand values. It can either be a stylized text-based logo or a graphic logo. 
    <br><br>
    For example, Apple primarily uses a graphic logo. Facebook uses a text-based logo. 
    <br><br>
    Once you have articulated your value statement and your name you will have an easier time making decisions about the logo and fonts.
    <br><br>
    At this point- after having nailed down a few aspects of your brand, there should be enough information to see a trend emerge. By this, I mean, a few natural characteristics in the name, the mission, the sound of the name, the letters used, and what you actually do. The next guiding principle to be introduced is:  
    <br><br>
    Try to make a list of the natural and unique characteristics present in your brand thus far. This is slightly abstract- but it is simpler than it sounds. What I mean is make a list of things like the letter 'T' is repeated in alliteration, if there are any rhymes, or numbers or unique sounds to the words. What we are trying to do is unpack the decisions you have already made in the previous two chapters. Many of the decisions made up until now have been made on feeling and gut impulses. This is ok. But now we are trying to unpack them. We want to unpack them to see objectively their natural characteristics so that we can exploit them.  By exploiting them you create a richer world of your brand, a sharpened language, and a tighter, more unified approach when you face the world. When a customer sees you in the crowd of other brands, you want to stick in their brains - the best way to do this is to focus on your key value and whatever natural sounds or shapes are in this. As your customers are getting to know you try to make them remember as few things as possible. So look at the little natural sounds or shapes in the names and values - and find ways to repeat them or express the same thing in different ways (I.e. Visually through a logo.) So treat the previous decisions as clues to follow to learn more about your brand.  
    <br><br>
    This is all an attempt to accentuate your eccentricities. 
    <br><br>
    An example to clarify this: 
    <br><br>
    The name for the design firm, OSSO, was chosen because it expressed many of our values. The name is short, phonetic. It only uses two letters and repeats both of them once. It is multi-cultural. In Italian and Portuguese, it means bone. This relates to our design sensibilities: bare bones, simple, structural, but strong and sustaining. So that is the name and the values expressed together. Now if I were looking at the natural characteristics and going to attempt to exploit it is would see: the simplicity of the name OSSO. Two letters. Both of the letters are very simple in shape, very geometric. O is a circle. S is a wave. I would notice the word is a palindrome - the same forward and backward. And as it happens the word is symmetrical left to right, right to left, top to bottom, and bottom to top. 
    <br><br>
    So how can we use these natural characteristics to restate the initial values of the brand? We could make patterns out of the shapes of O and S for our packaging and print collateral. Our business cards are blind embossed and left to be unclear which side is up. So when you have a business card that can be read from any direction- this communicates a new value: playfulness and thoughtfulness. It comes off as intellectual and a puzzle. These are all values we consciously want to communicate for OSSO. 
    <br><br>
    If your brand has numbers in the name, where can you repeat numbering? In the packaging to differentiate between different products. On your website to differentiate between pages. As you repeat a brand element it ties the others together and makes for a cohesive, unified, and memorable experience. 
    <br><br>
    If your name uses alliteration- where else can you use alliteration? Can the shape of the repeated letter be morphed into a graphic logo that further expresses your value? 
    <br><br>
    Another example of accentuating an eccentricity is Whole Foods' branding. Their value is natural, wholesomeness, quality, and health. This is expressed in the name. Coincidentally the word Whole has an 'o' in the middle. The shape of an O is the shape of a circle- which is associated with fullness, full circle. So the O becomes the basis for the logo. They illustrate the O to be in the shape of a fruit, with a leaf and stem. This is another natural coincidence that the most popular fruits are round, as is a full circle, as is the letter O which is at the very center of the word Whole. In other branding elements, Whole Foods uses a handwritten font, which has an O character that is a perfectly round O, like a circle. This is an example of accentuating your eccentricities to further illustrate and communicate your brand principles. 
    <br><br>
    The logo should draw upon the natural characteristics in your name that communicate your values. If it is about being elegant, what font and letter-shape can be accentuated to further express this? If it is about being simple what part of your name can express this value? 
    <br><br>
    This is the purpose of the logo- to further express your brand values by accentuating parts of your name. 
    <br><br>
    <blockquote>Accentuate your eccentricities. </blockquote>
    </p>
