    <h5 align="center">Chapter 5.</h5><h1 align="center">CONTENT</h1><br><br>
    <p>
    <span class="callout">As you fill in pieces of the corporate identity, a portrait should be appearing.</span> The personality of this portrait is largely determined by how it fits into the context of its industry. What makes you different on a personality level-- in terms of how you relate to your customers? 
    <br><br>
    Since you are partly conceived in the context of your industry and competition, part of your identity is formed negatively: I am liked Company X but more ____. 
    <br><br>
    <blockquote>Don't define yourself by your competition- but understand how you are different.  And why you are different in that particular way.</blockquote>
    <p>This is really another way of getting back to values. Your values determine who you are. Your hierarchy of values are different from other nearby brands, so in the mind of customers you take on a different 'personality'. Who you are, seen in the context of your competitors gives you a personality: you're the fun one or the elegant one or the serious one.  
    <br><br>
    Your personality is communicated initially through your logos and colors and name- then beyond this, through your imagery, voice, and other content. The way you make decisions about your voice and visual aesthetic is by following the principles you have already set down: the same guides you used to determine the name and logo extend to actual copywriting whether in advertising, web and print collateral or social media.  
    <br><br>
    <blockquote>The question again is: what is the customer looking to us for? Humor? Inspiration? Aspiration? An intellectual nudge?  </blockquote>
    <p>
    It is kind of abstract to think of brands in your category and having them line up before the customer for judgment-- but this is made concrete in feeds on social media. As your audience scrolls through their Twitter feed, you are standing next to a myriad of brands, entertainers, and new sources. You are truly side-by-side, being compared to brands and people within and beyond your category. Today you are expected to relate to customers on a much deeper level than before. You need to speak to them on many platforms and extend your brand through content that is only peripherally related to your product.
    <br><br>
    It is therefore of the utmost importance to know yourself: to know the characteristics, personality, and attributes you are expected to provide to your audience. Are you the funny friend? Are you the one they go to for advice on how to be sexy? To be cooler? Do they look to you to make them laugh or to Inform them on what is happening in Somalia?  
     <br><br>
    If your brand were an advisor to the customer (on a board along with every other brand they patronize) what role are you playing? Why are you on the board? To help them be more creative? Healthier? More thoughtful? More ethical? If the boardroom analogy doesn't resonate, try thinking of the marketplace of brands as a high school cafeteria. Who are you in that cafeteria? Why is your customer choosing to sit with you? Understanding the personality and human characteristics of your brand will help you understand how you should relate to your customer in the realm that is beyond the product.
    <br><br>
   <strong>This leads into your voice.</strong><br><br> Part of what content is about "What you talk about". The other part is about "How you talk about it." There are many different ways to talk about a single topic. How you discuss a topic matters hugely. This is your tone of voice. The tone you take in communicating with your audience is another important step in conveying your personality and values. Your tone can humanize you. It can make you relatable. It can make you aspirational. It can make you convivial or credible. So, in order to determine your tone, you must first decide how you want your customers and audience to conceive you. Are you like a doctor prescribing an antidote? Are you a friend offering a tip? Are you the cool expert letting them in on the next big trend? <br><br>
Once you have an answer to the way you want to relate to your customer, you can start to answer how that comes to life through tone of voice. This will drive you towards a very specific way of talking. Your voice will come through on your website, packaging, collateral-- through all communication with the world.
You must know how you talk. You must distinctly say: we are this not that. We are always x and never Y.
When you accomplish this, it will further materialize your personality in the mind of the customer. When they can conceive of you cohesively they will trust you, remember you, and be able to seek you for certain specific needs that they will have throughout their lives.
    </p>
