    <h5 align="center">Chapter 6.</h5><h1 align="center">DIGITAL</h1><br><br>
    <p>
      Your website is a map that mirrors the thought process of your customer. You must understand the thought process of how they went from looking for a t-shirt, to looking at your t-shirt. So the user-interface of your website should understand the user's journey, and now that they have arrived here, you can shepherd them home to the checkout.
      <br><br>
      The user's journey is a lot like the hero's journey. It has been long, frustrating, and arduous. And just when they are about to give up all hope, just when they think they will never find the thing they have been looking for, they see a glimpse of you. You seem to share their values- in certain non-verbal cues you are sending. This draws them in further. The product looks good, and it is delivered to them in a way that seems to understand their frustrations. It speaks to them without using words. It just feels right. And now that they have swirled so far down the funnel, and miraculously landed on your doorstep, you must invite them in. 
      <br><br>
      <blockquote>You need to know the thought process of your customer better than they do themselves. This is how you guide them.</blockquote>
      <p>
      Understand the thought process of your customer. What are they looking for (experientially)? What has the journey been like? And how is your buying process serving their needs in ways others did not? How are you shepherding them to the finish line? If you can write it out in a step by step process this will help.
      <br><br>
      A bad example of an e-commerce experience is the way most websites handle it. Most websites organize their clothing by category: tops, bottoms, outerwear etc. This is a good and natural filter but it is not a very engaging way to satisfy the customer’s search. It only works to a point. The larger your site gets, the wider your product offering grows, the more overwhelming it is. Customers already have had to filter so many other brands and things to arrive at your shop, the filtering process should not feel like it is starting over again. This pushes brands to focus their offerings. Do one thing really well. Customers today want to shop this way. They want brands to be bite-size. They want to go to one place for one specific thing. They want shopping to be like an app.
      <br><br>
      This is hard for brands with a fully-developed product line in multiple different categories.But as much as you can, you should break down your categories and think of them in basic principles. If you offer, shoes, shirts, and coats, approach each one independently because the way people buy shoes is different from the way they buy shirts. Break up categories into the way a customer thinks about them— then put it all back together. 
      <br><br>
      What is the most relevant divider for your customer? Are they looking for something for hiking as opposed to the beach? This reverts back to the value statement. If your value is that you offer products for specific activities, it is more relevant to your customers to divide your offering by activity than by top or bottom. So analyze your value statement in the context of your customer’s journey. They are frazzled and frustrated. Shopping is a means to an end. It is like dating. The real goal is to find your match. The fun part for your customer is getting to use or wear the thing. So how can you cut through the noise and touch them, surprise them, and shepherd them home?
    </p>
