      <h5 align="center">Chapter 7.</h5><h1 align="center">PACKAGING</h1><br><br>
      <p>
        Packaging is often the first tactile experience a customer will have with your brand. 
        <br><br>
        They have seen your website and your social media. They have experienced your brand and the sense of life you have created, but only digitally. You have done enough to entice them to take a chance and order your product. The mail comes, and there it is. 
        <br><br>
        It is another first impression. 
        <br><br>
        You and your customer have been flirting online, but this is the first real meeting. Here they can see if you were honest, if you embellished certain aspects of your personality, if you lied about how classy you actually are. Finally, they can see beyond the photoshopped photos and the marketing language and make a judgment for themselves. So you should take care to not let them down.
        <br><br>
        The language of packaging is spoken in textures, colors, folds, twists, and tucks. There are boxes, bottles, and bags. There are many physical requirements related to packaging that make much packaging design feel the same. But this is an opportunity. 
        <br><br>
        Every time you are lined up next to other brands is an opportunity to stand out. All you have to do is say something. Most packaging just sits there. The package smothers the product, cutting off all emotion, muting the communication of any personality or feeling.
        <br><br>
        But cardboard communicates values. 
        <br><br>
        <blockquote>Every material whispers something different. So use it to further express your values and tell your story.</blockquote>
        <p>
        You communicate emotion through the different materials you select and through the way you design the unboxing moment. The unboxing moment is the reveal, the moments of anticipation the customer feels as they open your packaging and see the product for the first time. 
        <br><br>
        Think about all of the emotions you want them to feel as they go through this process. How can you extend this moment? How can you accentuate it with different steps or touch-points? You can extend the moment by building in elements that heighten the anticipation: maybe it is a string they must untie in order to open the next layer of packaging. You can increase the wonder and delight by hiding 'Easter eggs' or hidden messages underneath different flaps. 
        <br><br>
        <blockquote>Packaging is a lot like theater. You are designing this mini performance for the customer. And you are hoping to make them say, at the end of, 'Wow, that was cool' or sleek or sexy.
        </blockquote><p>
        So work backward from that emotion and design an unboxing moment that will delight them enough to share it with at least one person.
      </p>
