<!-- CONCLUSION -->
      <div id="conclusion" class="chapter">
      <h1 align="center">CONCLUSION</h1><br><br>
      <p>
        These chapters have been exercises in articulating the words or emotions that you are bringing to the table.
        <br><br>
        Now, you have gone through the self-discovery to find the fantasy you are, the personality you are, the boardroom member you are, the emotion you are-- the value you are. Now BE that. Be more that than anyone else can be. Maybe it is elegance or intelligence or sexiness or futuristic. In everything you do, ask again and again what is the best way to evoke that?  Try to focus it down to one specific feeling. 
        <blockquote>
        Be an archetype. </blockquote>
        <p>
        Being an archetype means focusing the feeling you are trying to evoke to the maximum. It means knowing who you are, understanding the role you are playing in the mind of the customer, and fulfilling that and nothing else.
        <br><br>
        Many people and brands have a fear of being pigeonholed or stereotyped. They think it will be limiting, reductive, or cut off future business potential or market-share. But being an archetype, does not limit the business from expanding. Understanding the one specific emotion you appeal to is liberating. It means you don't have to try to be anything else to anyone else. It means you don't have to jump through the hoops of appealing to people you don't understand. It means you can be you. You are your values. Be them.
        <br><br>
        All of the best and most successful brands have become archetypes. Most middling brands suffer because they don't evoke anything particular in the mind of the customer. They don't make you feel much of anything. You feel a little of this, a little of that. It is like the person at the party who knows everyone but is close to no one. These brands make many shallow connections without having any real fans. They don't own up to any one feeling. They don't embrace their own values. This is much more deadly to a brand than being too focused.
        <br><br>
        The best brands become their values. By being your values, you become the rally point for anyone else who share those values. Be the rally point. 
        <br><br>
        This doesn't mean being boring. It is not paring down your personality or ambitions.
        <blockquote>
        Clarify don't simplify. </blockquote>
        <p>
        Simplifying is about reducing, stifling yourself, and cutting away.
        <br><br>
        Clarifying is about focusing on the message and getting everything out of the way that does not further it.
        <br><br>
        Clarify your purpose; be an archetype. 
        <br><br>
        Your brand is the God of elegance or athleticism or nostalgia. Your logo, your colors, your language, your packaging all must convey this. The main reason a brand is weak is because it never articulates the primary emotion it is trying to elicit. It never truly understands the reason the customer connects with it and purchases what it is selling. If you don't know the answer to this, you can't design a strong logo or packaging solution or website. Your decisions will be grasping attempts in the dark. You will come off as a scattered, nebulous collection of half-formed ideas. You will be building your future on a wobbly foundation, like trying to build a tent without having a tentpole.
        <br><br>
        Start with the tentpole.
        <br><br>
        You can be the God of anything. But you have to commit to it. You can't switch halfway and decide you want to be the God of something completely different. You can't covet other brands and wish to be the God of something else. You are the God of your chief value. It is already within you. This is why it all begins and ends with values. Values are what drove you into this mess in the first place. The feeling that was so strong it pushed you to venture forth and risk all kinds of things. This is your Genesis. Don't forget it.
        <br><br>
        By understanding more concretely what you value and why you value it, then seeing other brand decisions through this lens, you should be able to go forward and communicate it clearly and consistently. 
        <br><br>
       <blockquote> Take hold of your chief value. Clutch it in your arms as you move forward.</blockquote>
        <br><br><p>
        If you are feeling lost, start at the beginning again. Look within. Everything starts with values. Everything ends with values.
        <br><br><br><br>
      </p>
